er shows how this view of the modern body sought to extend the aesthetic experience beyond the boundaries imposed by rationalized life and to transcend these limits in search of ecstasy. With the help of much unpublished or long-forgotten archival material (including many little-known photographs), he investigates the process of constructing an "empire" of appropriative impulses toward ecstasy. Toepfer presents the work of such well-known figures as Rudolf Laban, Mary Wigman, and Oskar Schlemmer, along with less-known but equally fascinating body culture practitioners. His book is certain to become required reading for historians of dance, body culture, and modernism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBody imagexGermany. 0aBody imagezGermany. 0aDancexHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aDancexHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aDancezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aNudismxSociological aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudismxSociological aspectsxHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudismzGermanyxSociological aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aNudity in dancexHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudity in dancexHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudity in dancezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysical education and trainingxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aPhysical education and trainingxHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aPhysical education and trainingzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 4aEuropean history. 4aarchitecture. 4aculture. 4aempire. 4afilm. 4afreedom. 4ahistory of architecture. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4aliberty. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asocial philosophy. 4athe arts. 4awars. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aart history.  aart movements.  aart.  aberlin.  abody c